# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: combining-diacritical-marks
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] In digital typography, **combining characters** are characters that are intended to modify other characters.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] The most common combining characters in the Latin script are the **combining diacritical marks** (including **combining accents**).
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Unicode also contains many precomposed characters, so that in many cases it is possible to use both combining diacritics and precomposed characters, at the user's or application's choice.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] This leads to a requirement to perform Unicode normalization before comparing two Unicode strings and to carefully design encoding converters to correctly map all of the valid ways to represent a character in Unicode to a legacy encoding to avoid data loss.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] In Unicode, the main block of combining diacritics for European languages and the International Phonetic Alphabet is U+0300–U+036F.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Combining diacritical marks are also present in many other blocks of Unicode characters.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] In Unicode, diacritics are always added after the main character (in contrast to some older combining character sets such as ANSEL), and it is possible to add several diacritics to the same character, including stacked diacritics above and below, though some systems may not render these well.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Combining characters are not limited to these blocks; for instance, the combining dakuten (U+3099) and combining handakuten (U+309A) are in the Hiragana block, the Devanagari block contains combining vowel signs and other marks for use with that script, and so forth.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Combining characters are assigned the Unicode major category "M" ("Mark").
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] U+034F is the "combining grapheme joiner" (CGJ) and has no visible glyph.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Codepoints U+035C–0362 are double diacritics, diacritic signs placed across two letters.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Codepoints U+0363–036F are medieval superscript letter diacritics, letters written directly above other letters appearing in medieval Germanic manuscripts, but in some instances in use until as late as the 19th century.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] For example, U+0364 is an *e* written above the preceding letter, to be used for (Early) New High German umlaut notation, such as *uͤ* for Modern German *ü*.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] OpenType has the *ccmp* "feature tag" to define glyphs that are compositions or decompositions involving combining characters, the *mark* tag to define the positioning of combining characters onto base glyph, and *mkmk* for the positionings of combining characters onto each other.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] Combining characters have been used to create Zalgo text, which is text that appears "corrupted" or "creepy" due to an overuse of combining characters.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] This causes the text to extend vertically, overlapping other text.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] This is mostly used in horror contexts on the Internet.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-character] It is typically very challenging for most software to render, so the combining marks are often reduced or completely stripped off.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-diacritical-marks-for-symbols] Its block name in Unicode 1.0 was simply **Diacritical Marks for Symbols**.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] The **combining grapheme joiner** (CGJ), U+034F ͏ COMBINING GRAPHEME JOINER (&#847;) is a Unicode character that has no visible glyph and is "default ignorable" by applications.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] Its name is a misnomer and does not describe its function: the character does not join graphemes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] Its purpose is to semantically *separate* characters that should *not* be considered digraphs as well as to block canonical reordering of combining marks during normalization.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] For example, in a Hungarian language context, adjoining letters *c* and *s* would normally be considered equivalent to the cs digraph.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] If they are separated by the CGJ, they will be considered as two separate graphemes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] However, in contrast to the zero-width joiner and similar characters, the CGJ does not affect whether the two letters are *rendered* separately or as a ligature or cursively joined—the default behavior for this is determined by the font.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] The CGJ is also needed for complex scripts.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] For example, in most cases the Hebrew cantillation accent metheg is supposed to appear to the left of the vowel point and by default most display systems will render it like this even if it is typed before the vowel.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] But in some words in Biblical Hebrew the metheg appears to the right of the vowel, and to tell the display engine to render it properly on the right, CGJ must be typed between the metheg and the vowel.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] In the case of several consecutive combining diacritics, an intervening CGJ indicates that they should not be subject to canonical reordering.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/combining-grapheme-joiner] In contrast, the "zero-width non-joiner" (at U+200C in the General Punctuation range) prevents two adjacent characters from turning into a ligature.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In linguistics, a **grapheme** is the smallest functional unit of a writing system.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] The word *grapheme* is derived from Ancient Greek's *gráphō* ('write'), and the suffix *-eme* (by analogy with *phoneme* and other emic units).
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] The study of graphemes is called *graphemics*.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] The concept of a grapheme is abstract; it is similar to the notion of a character in computing.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] (A specific geometric shape that represents any particular grapheme in a given typeface is called a glyph.) In orthographic and linguistic notation, a particular glyph (character) is represented in graphemic notation by enclosing it within angle brackets: e.g. ⟨a⟩.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] There are two main opposing grapheme concepts.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In the so-called *referential conception*, graphemes are interpreted as the smallest units of writing that correspond with sounds (more accurately phonemes).
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In this concept, the *sh* in the written English word *shake* would be a grapheme because it represents the phoneme /ʃ/.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] This referential concept is linked to the *dependency hypothesis* that claims that writing merely depicts speech.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] By contrast, the *analogical concept* defines graphemes analogously to phonemes, i.e. via written minimal pairs such as *shake* vs.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In this example, *h* and *n* are graphemes because they distinguish two words.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] This analogical concept is associated with the autonomy hypothesis which holds that writing is a system in its own right and should be studied independently from speech.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In newer concepts, in which the grapheme is interpreted semiotically as a dyadic linguistic sign, it is defined as a minimal unit of writing that is both lexically distinctive and correspondent to a linguistic unit (phoneme, syllable, or morpheme).
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Graphemes are often notated within angle brackets: e.g. ⟨a⟩.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] This is analogous to the slash notation /a/ used for phonemes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Analogous to the square bracket notation [a] used for phones, glyphs are sometimes denoted with vertical lines, e.g. |ɑ|.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Thus, a grapheme can be regarded as an abstraction of a collection of glyphs that are all functionally equivalent.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] For example, in written English (or other languages using the Latin alphabet), the lowercase Latin letter "a" can appear in different typographic forms.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Since substitution of one form for another usually does not change the meaning of a word, they are considered to be allographs of the same grapheme, which can be written ⟨a⟩.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Similarly, the grapheme corresponding to "Arabic numeral zero" has a unique semantic identity and Unicode value `U+0030` but has variations such as how circular it is drawn or even the slashed zero form.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Italic and bold face forms are also allographic, as is the variation seen in serif (as in Times New Roman) versus sans-serif (as in Helvetica) forms.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] There is some disagreement as to whether capital and lower case letters are allographs or distinct graphemes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Capitals are generally found in certain triggering contexts that do not change the meaning of a word: a proper name, for example, or at the beginning of a sentence, or all caps in a newspaper headline.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In other contexts, capitalization can determine meaning: compare, for example Polish and polish: the former is a language, the latter is for shining shoes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Some linguists consider digraphs like the ⟨sh⟩ in *ship* to be distinct graphemes, but these are generally analyzed as sequences of graphemes.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Non-stylistic ligatures, however, such as ⟨æ⟩, are distinct graphemes, as are various letters with distinctive diacritics, such as ⟨ç⟩.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Identical glyphs may not always represent the same grapheme.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] For example, the three letters ⟨A⟩, ⟨А⟩ and ⟨Α⟩ appear identical but each has a different meaning: in order, they are the Latin letter A, the Cyrillic capital letter A and the Greek letter Alpha.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Each has its own code point in Unicode: U+0041 A LATIN CAPITAL LETTER A, U+0410 А CYRILLIC CAPITAL LETTER A and U+0391 Α GREEK CAPITAL LETTER ALPHA.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] For a full discussion of the different types, see Writing system § Functional classification.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] There are additional graphemic components used in writing, such as punctuation marks, mathematical symbols, word dividers such as the space, and other typographic symbols.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Ancient logographic scripts often used silent determinatives to disambiguate the meaning of a neighboring (non-silent) word.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] As mentioned in the previous section, in languages that use alphabetic writing systems, many of the graphemes stand in principle for the phonemes (significant sounds) of the language.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] In practice, however, the orthographies of such languages entail at least a certain amount of deviation from the ideal of exact grapheme–phoneme correspondence.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] A phoneme may be represented by a multigraph (sequence of more than one grapheme), as the digraph *sh* represents a single sound in English (and sometimes a single grapheme may represent more than one phoneme, as with the Russian letter я or the Spanish c).
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] "Shallow" orthographies such as those of standard Spanish and Finnish have relatively regular (though not always one-to-one) correspondence between graphemes and phonemes, while those of French and English have much less regular correspondence, and are known as deep orthographies.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] Multigraphs representing a single phoneme are normally treated as combinations of separate letters, not as graphemes in their own right.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] However, in some languages a multigraph may be treated as a single unit for the purposes of collation; for example, in a Czech dictionary, the section for words that start with ⟨ch⟩ comes after that for ⟨h⟩.
[src:combining-diacritical-marks/grapheme] For more examples, see Alphabetical order § Language-specific conventions.
